comments.author: Johnny R

comments.text:
It seems like a cool idea & I'll still watch it, but after JP3 I'm not 
holding high hopes for this one. They should have left it at the lost 
world. Even that one pushed it a little into Godzilla territory, but it was 
still rather good. I mean, resurrecting dinosaurs is one thing, but making 
a genetically modified, all new & approved killing machine for the fun of 
it after the events of the previous movies does seem a little implausible. 
The whole point of the park was to give the visitors an idea of what 
living, breathing dinosaurs from 65 million years ago looked & acted like 
in the flesh. Somewhere along the way, the late Michael Crichton's original 
idea got lost. Just an opinion, mind.﻿

comments.text:
If there were more herbivores than carnivores on average - it says a lot 
about 20th-21st century human mentality when *EVERY* Jurassic Park film has 
been dominated extremely violent, flesh-ripping carnivores. Here's a 
thought: How about a Jurassic Park with a more realistic feel and centered 
around the herbivores and other creatures. Q: Is it impossible to make. A: 
No. Q:  Would it be harder to make interesting for masses of brainless 
morons, thus requiring more intelligence, and less rat-racing and 
whoring-CGI graphics? A: You had better believe it would. Q: Would it 
require a more intelligent and patience audience. A: Naturally.﻿
